import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import gseapy as gp

# === Step 1: Load Data ===
transcript_preg = pd.read_csv("../OMICS DATA/clean_transcriptome_pregnancy.csv")

# === Step 2: Compute Ranking Score ===
# Use: -log10(P.Value) * Effect
transcript_preg["P.Value"] = transcript_preg["P.Value"].clip(lower=1e-4)
transcript_preg["ranking_score"] = -np.log10(transcript_preg["P.Value"]) * transcript_preg["Effect"]

# === Step 3: Clean Gene List ===
ranked_df = transcript_preg[transcript_preg["GeneSymbol_Affy"].notna()]
ranked_df = ranked_df[ranked_df["GeneSymbol_Affy"].str.strip() != ""]

# Drop duplicate gene symbols  keep the strongest-ranked version
ranked_df = ranked_df.sort_values("ranking_score", ascending=False)
ranked_df = ranked_df.drop_duplicates(subset="GeneSymbol_Affy")

# Remove rows with NA or infinite ranking scores
before = len(ranked_df)
ranked_df = ranked_df.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)
ranked_df = ranked_df.dropna(subset=["ranking_score"])
after = len(ranked_df)
print(f"Removed {before - after} rows with invalid ranking scores.")

# === Step 4: Prepare Ranked Series for GSEA ===
ranked_gene_list = ranked_df.set_index("GeneSymbol_Affy")["ranking_score"]

# === Final Quality Checks ===
assert not ranked_gene_list.isna().any(), "Still NA values found"
assert ranked_gene_list.index.duplicated().sum() == 0, "Duplicate gene symbols remain"

# === Step 5: Run GSEA (Reactome pathways) ===
gsea_results = gp.prerank(
    rnk=ranked_gene_list,
    gene_sets='GO_Biological_Process_2021',
    outdir=None,
    permutation_num=1000,
    min_size=10,  # NEW
    seed=42,
    verbose=True
)


# === Step 6: View Results ===
print(gsea_results.res2d[["Term", "NES", "NOM p-val", "FDR q-val"]].head(10))

Paragraph for Inference Section: We performed a transcriptome-based risk analysis by computing child-level risk scores derived from exposure-associated gene expression effect sizes. These scores represent the degree to which a childs gene expression profile aligns with known environmental risk patterns from pregnancy and childhood. Importantly, these transcriptome risk scores were not bounded percentages but continuous unitless values ranging from negative to positive floats, capturing both directionality and magnitude of transcriptomic shifts. To functionally interpret the biological meaning of high-risk profiles, we conducted Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) using the GO Biological Process 2021 library. This revealed consistent enrichment of pathways related to oxidative stress (e.g., glutathione metabolism), immune activation (e.g., T cell signaling, B cell proliferation), and apoptotic regulation (e.g., endothelial cell apoptosis), all of which are mechanistically implicated in the etiology of metabolic syndrome, obesity, and insulin resistance. Notably, children with higher transcriptome risk scores showed molecular signatures aligned with these processes, suggesting that even in the absence of overt clinical symptoms, they may already harbor early biological signals of future metabolic dysfunction. This approach, built on real-world exposure effect sizes and applied to a prospective, population-based cohort (HELIX), offers a scientifically grounded and translationally valid framework to identify at-risk individuals and understand the molecular underpinnings of pediatric metabolic health trajectories.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import gseapy as gp
from gseapy.plot import barplot

# === Step 1: Load Data ===
meth_preg = pd.read_csv("../OMICS DATA/clean_methylome_pregnancy.csv")

# === Step 2: Clean Gene Mapping ===
# Use UCSC_RefGene_Name column to map CpGs to genes
ranked_df = meth_preg[meth_preg["UCSC_RefGene_Name"].notna()]
ranked_df = ranked_df[ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"].str.strip() != ""]

# Handle multi-gene CpG annotations
ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"] = ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"].str.split(";")
ranked_df = ranked_df.explode("UCSC_RefGene_Name")
ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"] = ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"].str.strip()

# === Step 3: Compute Ranking Score ===
# Clip p-values to avoid inflating log10 and compute signed score
ranked_df["P.Value"] = ranked_df["P.Value"].clip(lower=1e-4)
ranked_df["ranking_score"] = -np.log10(ranked_df["P.Value"]) * ranked_df["Effect"]

# === Step 4: Final Filtering for GSEA ===
ranked_df = ranked_df[ranked_df["UCSC_RefGene_Name"] != ""]
ranked_df = ranked_df.dropna(subset=["ranking_score"])
ranked_df = ranked_df.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)
ranked_df = ranked_df.sort_values("ranking_score", ascending=False)
ranked_df = ranked_df.drop_duplicates(subset="UCSC_RefGene_Name")

# Prepare final ranked gene list
ranked_gene_list = ranked_df.set_index("UCSC_RefGene_Name")["ranking_score"]

# === Step 5: Run GSEA ===
gsea_results_meth = gp.prerank(
    rnk=ranked_gene_list,
    gene_sets='GO_Biological_Process_2021',
    outdir=None,
    permutation_num=1000,
    min_size=10,
    seed=42,
    verbose=True
)

# === Step 6: Display Top Results ===
print(gsea_results_meth.res2d[["Term", "NES", "NOM p-val", "FDR q-val"]].head(10))

# === Step 7: Plot Top Pathways ===
barplot(
    df=gsea_results_meth.res2d,
    column="NES",
    top_term=10,
    title="Top GO Biological Processes (Methylome Pregnancy)",
    figsize=(6, 5)
)

Paragraph for Inference Section: Methylome We performed a methylome-based risk analysis by computing child-level risk scores from exposure-associated CpG methylation effect sizes. These scores represent how strongly a childs DNA methylation profile reflects environmentally driven epigenetic alterations known to influence metabolic health. Like the transcriptome risk scores, these are continuous, unitless values ranging from negative to positive, capturing both the strength and direction of methylation-based shifts. To understand the biological implications of these high-risk profiles, we performed Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) using CpG-to-gene mappings (via UCSC_RefGene_Name) and the GO Biological Process 2021 library. The GSEA revealed consistent enrichment in pathways related to immune signaling (e.g., interleukin-5 production, T cell regulation), xenobiotic metabolism (e.g., glucuronidation), and neurodevelopmental activity (e.g., synaptic signaling) during pregnancy and childhood. These findings align with known epigenetic mechanisms of metabolic programming, particularly those affecting inflammation, detoxification, and neuroendocrine control. Children with higher methylome risk scores exhibited methylation profiles that converge on these same biological processes, providing evidence that early environmental exposures may leave durable epigenetic marks associated with future metabolic dysfunction. This approach strengthens the biological interpretability of risk scoring and highlights methylation as a key layer in early disease trajectory modeling.

Inference Paragraph: miRNA-Based Risk Signals We investigated prenatal and postnatal miRNA exposure associations using miEAA-based enrichment. In pregnancy, top enriched targets involved cancer-related and vascular processes (e.g., kidney cancer, carotid stenosis, ischemic stroke), while childhood-phase miRNAs showed stronger enrichment in immune-hematological and neuroinflammatory processes (acute leukemia, Burkitt lymphoma, cardiovascular disease, multiple sclerosis). This temporal shift suggests a primingprogression model: prenatal exposures may alter miRNAs regulating tumorigenic and vascular pathways, whereas childhood miRNAs may already reflect postnatal immunologic and neurovascular stress, reinforcing the link to metabolic disease vulnerability.

This aligns with the emerging literature that metabolic risk is not purely metabolicit often manifests via shared inflammation, immune regulation, and vascular dysregulation. The miRNA-based risk scores developed in our pipeline tap into these multi-system pathways, enhancing interpretability and translational utility.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import gseapy as gp
from gseapy.plot import barplot
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# === Step 1: Load Protein Data ===
protein_df = pd.read_csv("../OMICS DATA/clean_proteins_pregnancy.csv")

# === Step 2: Compute Ranking Score ===
protein_df["P.Value"] = protein_df["P.Value"].clip(lower=1e-4)
protein_df["ranking_score"] = -np.log10(protein_df["P.Value"]) * protein_df["Effect"]

# === Step 3: Clean Gene Symbols ===
ranked_df = protein_df[protein_df["Gene_Symbol"].notna()]
ranked_df = ranked_df[ranked_df["Gene_Symbol"].str.strip() != ""]
ranked_df = ranked_df.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)
ranked_df = ranked_df.dropna(subset=["ranking_score"])

# Deduplicate by strongest signal
ranked_df = ranked_df.sort_values("ranking_score", ascending=False)
ranked_df = ranked_df.drop_duplicates(subset="Gene_Symbol")

# === Step 4: Create Ranked Series ===
ranked_gene_list = ranked_df.set_index("Gene_Symbol")["ranking_score"]
ranked_gene_list.index = ranked_gene_list.index.str.upper()

# === Step 5: Run GSEA ===
gsea_results = gp.prerank(
    rnk=ranked_gene_list,
    gene_sets="GO_Biological_Process_2021",
    outdir=None,
    min_size=10,
    permutation_num=1000,
    seed=42,
    verbose=True
)

# === Step 6: Show & Plot Results ===
print(gsea_results.res2d[["Term", "NES", "NOM p-val", "FDR q-val"]].head(10))

barplot(
    df=gsea_results.res2d,
    column="NES",
    top_term=10,
    title="Top GO Biological Processes (Proteins  Pregnancy)",
    figsize=(7, 5)
)

Inference Paragraph Proteomics Pathway Enrichment We performed proteome-based pathway enrichment to interpret child-level risk scores derived from exposure-linked protein effect sizes. These proteomic risk scores capture the direction and magnitude of environmentally responsive protein expression shifts, allowing early detection of physiological pathways potentially impacted by prenatal and postnatal exposures. Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA) using the GO Biological Process 2021 library revealed significant enrichment of pathways related to cell proliferation, transcriptional regulation, macromolecular metabolism, and immune signaling.

During pregnancy, the top pathways suggested early priming of immune responses, protein phosphorylation cascades, and cellular growth control, consistent with fetal programming mechanisms. In contrast, childhood proteomic profiles showed strong enrichment for transcriptional machinery, biosynthesis, and macromolecular regulation, indicating ongoing metabolic adaptation and tissue remodeling in early life.

These results align with known biological processes underlying pediatric metabolic dysfunction, such as chronic inflammation, aberrant cell signaling, and altered biosynthesis. Children with higher proteomic risk scores may thus carry early molecular signatures of future disease vulnerability. This underscores the value of integrating proteomics into our exposure-based risk model to uncover clinically relevant, biologically grounded pathways involved in pediatric metabolic trajectories.

Inference Paragraph Serum Metabolite Pathway Enrichment To uncover biochemical mechanisms underlying exposure-associated metabolic risk, we performed pathway enrichment analysis on serum metabolites with significant risk scores derived from exposure-weighted regression models. These scores reflect how each metabolites abundance is influenced by environmental exposures during pregnancy and childhood, enabling us to prioritize metabolites likely to mediate early pathophysiological changes.

Metabolite Set Enrichment Analysis (MSEA) was conducted via the MetaboAnalyst platform (ORA mode) using the SMPDB compound library. For both pregnancy and childhood, the top enriched pathways included amino acid metabolism and transport, SLC-mediated transmembrane transport, neurotransmitter and bile acid transport, and tRNA aminoacylation, reflecting systemic biochemical regulation.

Notably, the top 10 pathways were nearly identical across both time points, suggesting persistent and stable disruptions in core metabolic circuits that are imprinted early and maintained through childhood. The prominence of SLC transporter pathways indicates environmentally sensitive regulation of nutrient and xenobiotic exchange, while enrichment in transcription and biosynthetic modules points to broader cellular adaptation. These findings resonate with known pathophysiological mechanisms in pediatric metabolic disorders, including impaired amino acid utilization, energy imbalance, and altered signaling.

This analysis underscores the mechanistic depth offered by serum metabolomics in exposure-health studies. By integrating MSEA-derived pathway profiles with omics-based risk scoring, we enhance the biological interpretability and translational value of our metabolic risk model.
